<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910423-0081</DOCNO><DOCID>910423-0081.</DOCID><HL>   Trigg, Ex-Chairman   Of Family Savings,   Sentenced to Prison</HL><DATE>04/23/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A federal judge here sentenced Oliver A.Trigg Jr., former chairman of Family Savings andamp; LoanAssociation, to seven years and three months in prison fordefrauding the thrift in order to acquire control of it.   Mr. Trigg, 40 years old, was convicted in February of 14criminal counts of conspiracy, bank fraud, money laundering,tax fraud and false statements related to his 1987 purchaseof control of the Los Angeles thrift.</LP><TEXT>   Federal prosecutors alleged in an indictment handed uplast September that Mr. Trigg, while serving as chairman butwithout equity in Family Savings, arranged for the thrift tolend $2.5 million to a third party for real estatedevelopment. Nearly half of that money was laundered into Mr.Trigg's personal bank account and used to buy a 51% stake inFamily Savings.   U.S. Judge Manuel Real also ordered Mr. Trigg to pay about$500,000 in restitution to Family Savings. The thrift had aloss of $3 million as a direct result of Mr. Trigg's crimesand another $3 million in lost deposits resulting fromdepositor fears that Family Savings would fail, according toformer Assistant U.S. Attorney Maurice A. Leiter, whoprosecuted the case.   James Cottle, 45, of Stockton, Calif., was convicted ofconspiracy and false statements for his role in assisting Mr.Trigg. He was sentenced last week to 60 days in prison, to beserved consecutively with a six-month charge imposed in arelated federal prosecution, according to the U.S. attorney'soffice in Los Angeles.</TEXT></DOC>